## What Is the ISC2 CGRC?

The CGRC — formerly known as the CAP, or Certified Authorization Professional — is a certification issued by ISC2, the same organization behind the well-known CISSP credential. The CGRC is specifically designed for professionals who work in governance, risk management, compliance, and system authorization — particularly within frameworks like NIST RMF.

The credential validates that someone can take an organization's security and compliance requirements and translate them into a real, functioning program — selecting appropriate controls, implementing them, assessing whether they work, and maintaining them over time. That is exactly the kind of work this challenge is built around.

The CGRC is organized into seven domains, and working through them today I was surprised — and honestly encouraged — by how much of what I have already covered aligns with the exam blueprint.

---

## The Seven CGRC Domains — and Where This Project Connects

**Domain 1 — Governance, Risk Management, and Compliance Program**

This domain covers how security and privacy programs align with business objectives, regulatory requirements, and organizational risk tolerance. It is essentially the conceptual foundation of GRC — the same ground I covered in Days 1 through 5 when I was building my understanding of what governance, risk, and compliance each mean and how they work together.

The key concepts here include risk appetite, policy hierarchy, stakeholder roles, and the relationship between compliance requirements and security objectives. Days 11 and 12 — covering GRC roles and governance document hierarchy — map directly to this domain.

**Domain 2 — Scope of the System**

This domain focuses on defining the boundaries of the system being assessed — what is included, what data it handles, how it connects to other systems, and how it should be categorized based on impact level. Day 17, where I mapped the OpenMRS architecture on AWS, is directly relevant here. Understanding what EC2, RDS, and S3 are doing and how they connect is exactly the kind of system scoping this domain requires.

Categorization — classifying ePHI as moderate to high impact based on the confidentiality, integrity, and availability requirements — is also part of this domain, which I first touched on in Day 6 when studying the NIST RMF.

**Domain 3 — Selection of Security and Privacy Controls**

Once a system is categorized, this domain covers how to select an appropriate set of controls from frameworks like NIST SP 800-53. The selection is not arbitrary — it is driven by the categorization and the specific risk environment of the system. Days 13 and 14, covering risk assessment and risk treatment, built the foundation for understanding why certain controls are selected over others. Day 18's HIPAA compliance checklist is a practical output of control selection thinking.

**Domain 4 — Implementation of Controls**

This domain covers what it actually means to put controls into place — configuring encryption, setting up access controls, deploying monitoring tools, and making the paper-based security plan into operational reality. Day 18 was heavily focused on this, working through what encryption means for each AWS component and what IAM, CloudTrail, and WAF implementation looks like for OpenMRS specifically.

This is the domain I feel I have the most still to learn in practical terms. Understanding that encryption needs to be enabled is one thing. Configuring it correctly, verifying it is working, and troubleshooting it when it is not are skills that require hands-on practice. That is part of what this project is building toward.

**Domain 5 — Assessment and Audit of Controls**

This domain covers how to verify that controls are actually working — through testing, auditing, and independent assessment. It connects directly to Step 5 of the NIST RMF, which I covered on Day 6. The core principle is that implementation and verification are two separate activities, and skipping verification is how organizations end up with controls that exist on paper but fail in practice.

This is an area I have not yet covered in depth in this project. As I move into the later phases, I want to work through what a real control assessment looks like — what questions to ask, what evidence to collect, and how to document findings in a way that supports authorization decisions.

**Domain 6 — Authorization of the System**

This domain covers the formal risk acceptance process — the Authorizing Official reviewing assessment findings, understanding residual risk, and making a documented decision to authorize or deny operation. I covered this conceptually on Day 6 in the NIST RMF walkthrough, and on Day 11 when discussing the Authorizing Official role. The CGRC exam tests whether candidates understand this as a genuine risk management decision rather than a rubber stamp.

**Domain 7 — Continuous Monitoring**

This domain covers what happens after a system is authorized — ongoing monitoring, reassessment of controls, response to new threats, and maintaining the system's security posture over time. Days 16 and 18 touched on this through CloudTrail, CloudWatch, and the importance of treating security as an ongoing operational function rather than a one-time compliance exercise. Day 6's discussion of the NIST RMF Monitor step is the direct framework connection.

